The Revival of Great Leaders
London —— It has been two hundred years since the Battle of Waterloo, in which Napoleon's catastrophic defeat severely damaged France's self-esteem, so much so that General de Gaulle omitted any mention of this battle when writing France's military history.
Nevertheless, if you acknowledge that "greatness" is a personal quality, then both Napoleon and de Gaulle can be considered the greatest leaders in history.
Marx and Tolstoy would say that there is no such thing as a "great leader".
In Marx's view, the class struggle in France created the environment in which a "grotesque mediocrity" like Napoleon could become a hero.
In Tolstoy's view, Napoleon was not a particularly outstanding general, and his victories should be attributed to the courage and dedication of the French soldiers who fought in the Battle of Borodino.
Regardless of whether Napoleon was great, we need to clarify whether we can describe any leader as great.
If the answer is yes, then who can be described as great?
Political philosopher Isaiah Berlin believes that great leaders must meet two particularly important criteria.
First, is the leader able to recognize historical trends?
Otto von Bismarck did, as did his German compatriot Konrad Adenauer; borrowing Bismarck's unforgettable phrase, both heard "the rustling of the mantle of God."
Secondly, did the leader make important decisions?
Of course, if a leader is forced to make decisions, he or she cannot be blamed for them, nor can they take credit for them.
Therefore, the key is whether the leader had the opportunity to weigh the pros and cons and make the right decisions on behalf of the nation.
Therefore, de Gaulle certainly deserves a place on any list of great leaders.
Almost single-handedly, he led France out of the post-war decline.
After regaining power in 1958, he once again saved his country by suppressing two failed coups, ending the Algerian War, and drafting the Constitution of the Fifth Republic.
Like British Prime Minister Winston Churchill, de Gaulle gave the French a new worldview, establishing their position in the post-war global order.
In fact, the ultimate impact that de Gaulle and Churchill had in shaping their countries' worldviews was somewhat excessive.
Their successors viewed the world — and their own role in it — for years afterward in ways that constrained rational inquiry and distorted decision-making.
The result was that leaders of both countries afterwards were never able to achieve accomplishments comparable to those of the two great leaders.
But there is still one British prime minister who can be compared to them: she is Margaret Thatcher, a very controversial figure, liked by as many people as those who dislike her.
Even her resignation 25 years ago stemmed from resistance within her own cabinet and party.
But it is not necessary to be loved by everyone to be a great leader.
In fact, even her critics cannot deny her impact.
Alongside being Britain's first female prime minister and nearly the earliest female prime minister in other countries as well, Thatcher helped turn around Britain's economic decline.
Moreover, her offensive against overly powerful unions enhanced the manageability of the country at a time when it seemed to be sliding into turmoil and chaos.
Given this, she undoubtedly has the right to be considered a candidate for "great leader."
Similarly, although far from flawless, Deng Xiaoping of China is also qualified to be considered a great leader.
Aside from assisting Mao Zedong in doing evil, Deng played a decisive role in ordering the 1989 Tiananmen Square massacre.
But Deng also revitalized the market, leading China on an unprecedented path of development and prosperity that ultimately lifted hundreds of millions of Chinese people out of poverty.
Many people consider Lee Kuan Yew, the founder and long-serving prime minister of Singapore, to be a great leader, although he may have wished to showcase his talents on a larger stage.
In fact, the size of a country does not seem to affect whether a person can become a great leader.
I had no intention of being disrespectful when I said that a small country like Luxembourg is unlikely to produce a great leader, especially given the country's generally low level of political controversy.
The vast territory of the United States is more than sufficient to be a cradle for great leaders.
Some presidents have indeed been quite accomplished.
Harry Truman and Dwight Eisenhower — though not intellectual giants — demonstrated remarkable judgment in establishing the postwar international order that supported world peace for decades.
Others, including Ronald Reagan and Bill Clinton, possessed high talent — namely, the ability to inspire and the art of persuasion.
John F. Kennedy had both qualities.
He completed a great task: resolving the Cuban Missile Crisis.
His gift for inspiration was unparalleled; in fact, his assassination after his death consolidated the tradition he left behind.
In South Africa, no one has yet been regarded as a great figure since the death of President Mandela, who combined courage, authority, and magnanimous grace.
Indeed, he was the most charming leader I have ever seen; the other two — former UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan and former U.S. Secretary of State Colin Powell — are either Africans or African Americans.
What about today?
The only one qualified to claim greatness is the de facto leader of the European Union, German Chancellor Angela Merkel.
Like former Chancellor Helmut Kohl, she was often underestimated at the beginning but made few mistakes when making important decisions.
Kohl formulated generous terms for German unification; Merkel stood up to Putin when he invaded Ukraine and adopted a tolerant approach to the immigration crisis.
I think Marx and Tolstoy are wrong.
Political leaders — those who exercise political power — can change the situation, whether for the better or worse.
Merkel is today's most obvious example, as she has pointed the way for Europe to deal with a difficult survival crisis.
